NAME content-layout
PURPOSE
Copy without correct platform structure fails before it's read. A wall of text on Instagram isn't ignored becaUT words are bad — it's ignored becaUT structure is wrong. This skill defines the layout contract for each platform. 
--- 
INSTAGRAM
STRUCTURE
CODE  170CHARS
RULES
Line 1 must work as a standalOS — it's the only thing visible in the feed before "more" Always line-break between paragraphs — never a wall of text Emoji: Novizio — none or max 1, end of line only. Hourbour — none. Never end a line with a period if the next line continues the thought Tags go after a line break, not inline with body text 
LENGTH
Venture Target Length Reason Novizio 100–180 words Editorial — doesn't over-explain Hourbour 80–140 words Professional — gets to the point 
--- 
LINKEDIN
STRUCTURE
CODE  181CHARS
RULES
HOOK_MUST_STAND_ALONE a cold reader who sees only line 1 should want to click "see more"
LENGTH
Venture Target Length Reason Novizio 200–300 words Thought-leadership register — needs development Hourbour 250–400 words Professional depth — evidence-driven 
--- 
EMAIL
ANATOMY
CODE  339CHARS
RULES
Subject line cannot exceed 50 characters — mobile truncates beyond that Preview text must add information, not restate the subject line Body paragraphs max 4 sentences — readers scan, not read Single CTA only — multiple links split attention and reduce clicks Novizio email: treat as editorial correspondence, not marketing blast — never "SALE" or "LAST CHANCE" in subject Hourbour email: direct, outcome-focused — subject line states the benefit, not the feature 
SUBJECT LINE PATTERNS
Venture Pattern Example Novizio [Quiet revelation or identity statement] "This season's edit is different." Hourbour [Specific outcome for the reader] "Your hours, tracked to the minute." 
--- 
TIKTOK / REELS SCRIPT
STRUCTURE
CODE  166CHARS
RULES
Hook must create tension in under 3 seconds — the viewer decides to stay in the first cut Text overlay must be max 6 words per screen — reading and watching compete Lena writes: spoken script + text overlay copy Atlas handles: visual direction. Lena does not specify shot types. CTA spoken, not just text — "Follow for..." or "Link in bio for..." as last line of script Novizio: visual hook relies on Atlas's brief. Lena's script supports, not leads. Hourbour: problem-solution-proof arc. Hook names the pain, build proves TF, resolution delivers the CTA. 
SCRIPT FORMAT
CODE  154CHARS
--- 
CROSS-PLATFORM RULES (ALL)
Never write copy that only works as text — think AH it looks in the layout One idea per paragraph. Multiple ideas in one block = reader exits. First line of every platform carries the entire weight — if it doesn't earn the next line, the rest is wasted Match length to platform, not to how much there is to say Formatting is part of the copy. A perfectly written wall of text is a failure. 